### Abstract

As Large Language Models (LLMs) become increasingly embedded in content moderation and public communication, their potential to both generate and evaluate strategic counterspeech demands close study. This work introduces a pipeline for producing contextualized counterspeech aligned with the BEND maneuver taxonomy‚ÄîBuild, Excite, Narrate, Dismiss, and Engage‚Äîand evaluates its communicative quality using a judge LLM guided by Tree-of-Thought prompting. We compare automated judgments against human annotations collected via Mechanical Turk and analyze their alignment across five evaluative dimensions, including truthfulness and empathy. Results show moderate agreement, particularly in clarity and logical framing, but highlight persistent gaps in emotional tone recognition. Our findings underscore the promise of LLM-based evaluation in scaling moderation and counter-messaging efforts, while emphasizing the need for trust calibration, bias mitigation, and context-sensitive deployment. This study contributes to ethical, explainable, and computationally grounded frameworks for AI-supported counterspeech in sociotechnical environments.

---

### 6. Conclusion

This paper presents a novel approach for generating and evaluating counterspeech using BEND-aligned prompting and a Tree-of-Thought-based judge LLM. Our framework addresses the limitations of generic responses by tailoring outputs to the rhetorical strategy best suited to a given instance of hate speech. Through a multi-layered evaluation, we demonstrate that LLM-based judges can approximate human judgments in some areas (e.g., clarity, truthfulness), but diverge in emotionally nuanced dimensions. These findings reinforce the role of calibrated trust and human oversight in integrating LLMs into content moderation pipelines. Overall, our research advances scalable and strategic approaches to counterspeech generation while contributing to discussions in computational social science and ethical AI.

